rmans and introduced by them to Britain. In the later Middle Ages it was reanalysed by folk etymology as if from Latin <i>rosa munda</i> ‘pure rose’ or <i>rosa mundi</i> ‘rose of the world’, titles given to the Virgin Mary. The spelling  <b>Rosamond</b>  has been common since the Middle Ages, when scribes used <i>o</i> for <i>u</i>, to distinguish it from <i>n</i> and <i>m</i>, all of which consisted of very similar downstrokes of the pen. ‘Fair Rosamond’ (  Rosamond Clifford ) was a legendary beauty who lived at Woodstock in Oxfordshire in the 12th century. She is said to have been the mistress of  King Henry II , and to have been murdered by the queen,  Eleanor of Aquitaine , in  1176 ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":1,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":11,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":21,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Rosamond de Novant was born about 1085, in Somerset, England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Novant, was 27 and her mother, Jean of Cornwall, was 21. She married Gilbert